> remove(): It removes the element x from the set. it x is not present in set, it returns a key error. The .remove(x) operation returns None.
> discard(): It removes the element x from the set. it x is not present in set, it does not returns a key error, but returns none
> pop(): removes an arbitrary element from set, if there is no element in set, it returns key error

> PROBLEM:
You have a non-empty set S, and you have to execute N  commands given in  N lines.
The commands will be pop, remove and discard.

The first line contains integer n , the number of elements in the set s .
The second line contains n space separated elements of set s . All of the elements are non-negative integers, less than or equal to 9.
The third line contains integer N , the number of commands.
The next  lines contains either pop, remove and/or discard commands followed by their associated value.

> SOLUTION: 
n = int(input())
s = set(map(int, input().split()))

N = int(input())


for _ in range(N):
    commands = input().split()

    if commands[0]=="pop":
        s.pop()
    elif commands[0]=="remove":
        try:
            s.remove(int(commands[1]))
        except KeyError:
            pass
            
    else: 
        s.discard(int(commands[1]))
            
print(sum(s))
